    <item>
      <title>Applying First Principles to Multidisciplinary Engineering</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/articles/first-principles-aerospace/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 20 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/articles/first-principles-aerospace/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h3 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;The Fundamental Breakdown&#xD;&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;the-fundamental-breakdown&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xD;&#xA;    &#xD;&#xA;    &lt;span&#xD;&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xD;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#the-fundamental-breakdown&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xD;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xD;&#xA;    &#xD;&#xA;&lt;/h3&gt;&#xD;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;In the pursuit of advanced aerospace systems, we often become entirely consumed by the mechanical hardware—thrust, drag, computational fluid dynamics, and material tensile strength. However, any system designed to carry or support human life must ultimately answer to the constraints of biology.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Through my independent studies into anatomy, physiology, and pathology, I have realized that the human body is the most complex mechanical system we will ever encounter.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
